Implement Slice 16 only: Product UI/UX Refinement Pass 2.

Before coding, read:
1. AGENTS.md
2. docs/mvp-requirements.md
3. docs/decisions.md
4. docs/slices.md

Context:
The app already has a better Google/Firebase-inspired direction, but it still needs refinement in loading states, login presentation, sidebar behavior, account menu behavior, action feedback, permit detail actions, and chip/card information hierarchy.

Important:
This is a UI/UX refinement slice only.
Do not change business logic.
Do not change Firestore models.
Do not change Firestore rules.
Do not change permit workflow.
Do not add dependencies.
Do not rewrite the app.
Keep desktop, mobile, and dark mode in mind.

Goals:
Refine the app into a more mature, calm, polished internal product experience.

1. Login screen refinement
- The login page currently feels too plain and too empty.
- Keep it simple, but add a subtle branded ambient background aligned with the app identity.
- Use a soft background treatment:
  - very light gradient and/or soft radial glow
  - subtle pattern/shape if needed
  - must remain eye-comfortable
  - must work in dark mode too
- Keep the login card clean and professional.
- Do not turn it into a marketing landing page.
- Do not add noisy graphics.

2. Animated loading system
- Replace plain loading text with a proper animated loading system.
- Introduce consistent loading patterns:
  - button loading spinner for actions like signing in / saving / submitting
  - skeleton loading for cards, tables, detail sections
  - optional subtle linear progress for page/section loading
- Use calm professional animations.
- Do not use playful or decorative animations.
- Apply this to:
  - login submit
  - permit details load
  - dashboard sections
  - activity log
  - permit list/table/cards
  - forms where loading is relevant

3. Sidebar refinement
- Make the desktop sidebar sticky/fixed during scroll.
- Replace the bottom “Collapse” button with a better Firebase-style collapse solution.
- Use a top-area control for collapse/expand.
- Support rail mode when collapsed:
  - icons visible
  - active item visible
  - tooltips if simple
- Collapse/expand must be smooth.
- There must always be a clear way to expand again.
- Keep mobile behavior separate: no collapsible desktop-style sidebar on mobile.

4. Account control and dropdown refinement
- Refine the account chip padding/alignment.
- Add a visible dropdown indicator (e.g. chevron).
- Dropdown menu should close when:
  - clicking outside
  - pressing Escape
  - selecting a menu item
- Keep the menu aligned and polished.
- Maintain accessibility and keyboard friendliness.

5. Chip/badge refinement
- Current rounded status chips are still too colorful and distracting.
- Reduce visual noise.
- Introduce a calmer chip system:
  - workflow status = highest emphasis
  - expiry state = medium emphasis
  - risk = lower emphasis
  - checklist checked/unchecked = low emphasis but still descriptive
- Use softer backgrounds, subtle borders, and readable text.
- Avoid bright saturated colors.
- Do not make every chip look equally important.

6. Dashboard and permit cards refinement
- Improve information hierarchy in dashboard cards and recent permit cards.
- Reduce clutter.
- Permit cards should feel more professional and easier to scan.
- Recommended structure:
  - permit number
  - primary status
  - key metadata
  - secondary metadata
  - clear action
- Do not let every line compete visually.
- Use spacing and hierarchy more than color.

7. Permit table refinement
- Keep desktop table calm and professional.
- Reduce chip noise inside the table.
- Improve scanability with spacing/alignment.
- Keep filters compact and clean.
- Do not let the table feel overly colorful.

8. Permit details refinement
- Reposition the Print / Save PDF action into a cleaner page action area.
- Keep it visible but not awkwardly mixed into the title block.
- Permit details page must use the new loading system.
- Checklist checked/unchecked state must be semantically correct:
  - checked should not be loud
  - unchecked should not use green
  - keep it calm and descriptive
- Maintain good desktop and mobile layout.

9. Action feedback system
- Introduce polished feedback patterns:
  - confirmation dialog for major actions (approve, reject, submit, logout if appropriate)
  - snackbar/toast for success and short feedback
  - inline validation for forms
- Replace raw/basic alert-like behavior with smooth consistent UI feedback.
- Keep it lightweight and dependency-free.

10. General requirements
- Preserve dark mode compatibility.
- Preserve print styles.
- Preserve role-aware navigation.
- Preserve desktop and mobile responsiveness.
- Do not change business logic.
- Do not add dependencies.

Before changing files:
- Briefly audit what still feels unpolished.
- Explain planned refinements.
- List likely files to change.

After changing files:
- Summarize exactly what changed.
- Confirm no business logic changed.
- Confirm no Firestore model/rules changes.
- Confirm no dependencies were added.
- Mention desktop/mobile/dark-mode impact.
- Run npm run build.

Expected result:
A calmer, more polished, more Google/Firebase-style product experience with a better login background, animated loading system, fixed smooth sidebar behavior, better account dropdown UX, less distracting chips, better permit card/table hierarchy, better permit detail actions, and a smooth dialog/snackbar feedback system.